Peel and grate the @garlic{1%clove} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Peel and grate the @ginger{1}(peeled and grated) (use a #teaspoon{} to easily scrape away the peel).

Quarter the @lime{1}.

In a #bowl{}, mix together the @Sweet Asian Sauce{2%sachet}, @soy sauce{1%sachet}, ginger, garlic,
juice from one lime wedge and @sugar{1%tsp} (double both for 4p).

Add the @beef strips{250%g} to the bowl and leave to marinate.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw meat and its packaging.

Halve the @bell pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Slice into thin strips.

Place a #large pan{} over high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Once the oil is hot, add the pepper and fry, stirring until just softened, ~{6-8%minutes}.

Meanwhile, boil a #pot{} of @water{to taste} for the noodles.

Add the @udon noodles{300%g} and cook until warmed through, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #sieve{} and pop back in the pot, off the heat.

Drizzle with oil and stir through to prevent sticking.

While the noodles cook, add the beef and marinade to the peppers and cook for ~{1-2%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Meat is safe to eat when the outside is browned.

> TIP: If you're in a hurry you can boil the water in your kettle.

Remove the pan from the heat, add the drained noodles and toss to coat.

Taste and season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}, if required.

Divide the noodles between bowls.

Finish the dish with a scattering of @peanuts{20%g}.

Serve remaining lime wedges alongside for squeezing over.